# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: austronesian-peoples
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The **2010 United States census** was the 23rd United States census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] National Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2010.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The census was taken via mail-in citizen self-reporting, with enumerators serving to spot-check randomly selected neighborhoods and communities.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] As part of a drive to increase the count's accuracy, 635,000 temporary enumerators were hired.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The population of the United States was counted as 308,745,538, a 9.7% increase from the 2000 United States census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 500,000 people as well as the first in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 200,000.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] It was the first census since 1930 that California did not record the largest population growth in absolute number.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Texas surpassed California's growth by 4.3 million to 3.4 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The 2000 U.S. census was the previous census completed.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census is required by law of people living in the United States in Title 13 of the United States Code.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] On January 25, 2010, Census Bureau Director Robert Groves personally inaugurated the 2010 census enumeration by counting World War II veteran Clifton Jackson, a resident of Noorvik, Alaska.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] More than 120 million census forms were delivered by the U.S.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The number of forms mailed out or hand-delivered by the Census Bureau was approximately 134 million on April 1, 2010.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census national mail participation rate was 74%.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] From April through July 2010, census takers visited households that did not return a form, an operation called "non-response follow-up" (NRFU).
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau delivered population information to the U.S. president for apportionment, and later in March 2011, complete redistricting data was delivered to states.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2082.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau did not use a long form for the 2010 census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In several previous censuses, one in six households received this long form, which asked for detailed social and economic information.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Were there any additional people staying here on April 1, 2010, that you did not include in Question 1?
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] What is Person 1's age and Person 1's date of birth?
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Is Person 1 of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin?
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Does Person 1 sometimes live or stay somewhere else?
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The form included space to repeat some or all of these questions for up to twelve residents total.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In contrast to the 2000 census, an Internet response option was not offered, nor was the form available for download.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Detailed socioeconomic information collected during past censuses will continue to be collected through the American Community Survey.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The survey provides data about communities in the United States on a 1-year or 3-year cycle, depending on the size of the community, rather than once every 10 years.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] A small percentage of the population on a rotating basis will receive the survey each year, and no household will receive it more than once every five years.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau announced that it would count same-sex married couples.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] However, the final form did not contain a separate "same-sex married couple" option.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] When noting the relationship between household members, same-sex couples who are married could mark their spouses as being "Husband or wife", the same response given by opposite-sex married couples.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] An "unmarried partner" option was available for couples (whether same-sex or opposite-sex) who were not married.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The Census 2010 Language Program was significantly expanded.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Language assistance in 49 languages in the 2000 Census was increased to 59 languages in Census 2000.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In addition to English, Census questionnaire was available in five non-English languages: Spanish, Chinese (simplified), Korean, Vietnamese, and Russian.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census cost $13 billion, approximately $42 per capita; by comparison, the 2010 census per-capita cost for China was about US$1 and for India was US$0.40.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Operational costs were $5.4 billion, significantly under the $7 billion budget.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In December 2010 the Government Accountability Office (GAO) noted that the cost of conducting the census has approximately doubled each decade since 1970.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In a detailed 2004 report to Congress, the GAO called on the Census Bureau to address cost and design issues, and at that time, had estimated the 2010 census cost to be $11 billion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Locke credited the management practices of Census Bureau director Robert Groves, citing in particular the decision to buy additional advertising in locations where responses lagged, which improved the overall response rate.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The agency also has begun to rely more on questioning neighbors or other reliable third parties when a person could not be immediately reached at home, which reduced the cost of follow-up visits.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census data for about 22% of U.S. households that did not reply by mail were based on such outside interviews, Groves said.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In 2005, Lockheed Martin won a six-year, $500 million contract to capture and standardize data for the census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The contract included systems, facilities, and staffing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The final value of that contract was in excess of one billion dollars.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Information technology was about a quarter of the projected $11.3 billion cost of the decennial census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The use of high-speed document scanning technology, such as ImageTrac scanners developed by IBML, helped Lockheed Martin complete the project on schedule and under budget.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Due to the rise in social media and cell-phone usage in the U.S., the Census Bureau used research gathered through a cell-phone study in order to target media and ads to populations that were nonrespondents and promote census participation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] This study also helped gauge the mindset of those who fail to respond, trying to figure out why.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census to use hand-held computing devices with GPS capability, although they were only used for the address canvassing operation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Enumerators (information gatherers) that had operational problems with the device understandably made negative reports.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] During the 2009 Senate confirmation hearings for Robert Groves, President Obama's Census Director appointee, there was much mention of contracting problems but very little criticism of the units themselves.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau chose to conduct the primary operation, Non-Response Follow Up (NRFU), without using the handheld computing devices.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] There was a penalty of $100 for not completing some or all of the 2010 U.S.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Robert Grove, however, wrote "the Census Bureau has rarely prosecuted failure to respond.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] While the rationale for the mandatory nature of the census still applies today, our message for the 2010 Census is about the common good benefits of participation".
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The fine for non-participation is much lower than that for reporting false information.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN) was given a contract to help publicize the importance of the census count and to encourage individuals to fill out their forms.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In September 2009, after controversial undercover videos showing four ACORN staffers giving tax advice to a man and a woman posing as a prostitute, the bureau canceled ACORN's contract.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Various American celebrities, including Demi Lovato and Eva Longoria, were used in public service announcements targeting younger people to fill out census forms.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Wilmer Valderrama and Rosario Dawson have helped spread census awareness among young Hispanics, a historically low participating ethnicity in the U.S. census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Rapper Ludacris also participated in efforts to spread awareness of the 2010 census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau hired about 635,000 people to find those U.S. residents who had not returned their forms by mail; as of May 28, 2010, 113 census workers had been victims of crime while conducting the census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Some political conservatives and libertarians questioned the validity of the questions and even encouraged people to refuse to answer questions for privacy and constitutional reasons.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] As a result, the Census Bureau undertook an unprecedented advertising campaign targeted at encouraging white political conservatives to fill out their forms, in the hope of avoiding an undercount of this group.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 U.S. census was the primary sponsor at NASCAR races in Atlanta, Bristol, and Martinsville, and sponsored the No.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] 16 Ford Fusion driven by Greg Biffle for part of the season, because of a marketing survey that indicated most NASCAR fans lean politically conservative.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] It also ran an advertisement during the 2010 Super Bowl, and hired singer Marie Osmond, who is thought to have many conservative fans, to publicize the census.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The results of the 2010 census determined the number of seats that each state received in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 2012 elections.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state had in the Electoral College for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Because of population changes, eighteen states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and ten states lost at least one seat.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The final result involved 12 seats being switched.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Some objected to the counting of persons who are in the United States illegally.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Senators David Vitter (R-LA) and Bob Bennett (R-UT) tried unsuccessfully to add questions on immigration status to the census form.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Organizations such as the Prison Policy Initiative argued that the census counts of incarcerated men and women as residents of prisons, rather than of their pre-incarceration addresses, skewed political clout and resulted in misleading demographic and population data.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Many residents of prisons counted on the 2010 census were those who identify as Black and Hispanic.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] This could lead to the loss of resources for underserved minority communities.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The term "Negro" was used in the questionnaire as one of the options for African Americans (Question 9.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Black, African Am., or Negro) as a choice to describe one's race.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau spokesman Jack Martin explained that "many older African-Americans identified themselves that way, and many still do.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Those who identify themselves as Negroes need to be included." The word was also used in the 2000 census, with over 56,000 people identifying themselves as "Negro".
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] In response to complaints over the word's inclusion on the 2010 census, the Census Bureau announced in 2013 that it would stop using "Negro" going forward, with the 2014 American Community Survey census form being the first without the word.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census contained ten questions about age, gender, ethnicity, home ownership, and household relationships.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Six of the ten questions were to be answered for each individual in the household.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Federal law has provisions for fining those who refuse to complete the census form.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Detroit Mayor Dave Bing held a press conference on March 22, 2011, to announce that the city would challenge its census results.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The challenge, being led by the city's planning department, cited an inconsistency as an example showing a downtown census tract which lost only 60 housing units, but 1,400 people, implying that a downtown jail or dormitory was missed in canvassing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] NYC Mayor Michael Bloomberg held a conference on March 27, 2011, to announce that the city would also challenge his city's census results, specifically the apparent undercounting in the boroughs of Queens and Brooklyn.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Bloomberg said that the numbers for Queens and Brooklyn, the two most populous boroughs, are implausible.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] According to the census, they grew by only 0.1% and 1.6%, respectively, while the other boroughs grew by between 3% and 5%.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] He also stated that the census showed improbably high numbers of vacant housing in vital neighborhoods such as Jackson Heights, Queens.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The District of Columbia announced in August 2011 that it would also challenge its census results.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The Mayor's Office claimed that the detailed information provided for 549 census blocks is "nonsensical", listing examples of census data that show housing units located in the middle of a street that does not actually exist.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] However, officials do not believe the city's total population will drastically change as a result of the challenge.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The state with the highest percentage rate of growth was Nevada, while the state with the largest population increase was Texas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] Michigan, the 8th largest by population, was the only state to lose population (although Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, lost population as well), and the District of Columbia saw its first gain since the 1950s.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] The resident populations listed below do not include people living overseas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] For Congressional apportionment, the sum of a state's resident population and its population of military personnel and federal contractors living overseas (but not other citizens overseas, such as missionaries or expatriate workers) is used.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] These are core metropolitan rankings versus combined statistical areas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/2010-united-states-census] For full list with current data, go to metropolitan statistics.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Founded in 2006, 23andMe was the first company to offer autosomal DNA testing for ancestry, an approach now used across the industry.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Its saliva-based genetic testing service was named "Invention of the Year" by *Time* in 2008.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The company had an early confrontational relationship with the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) over its health-related tests, which were suspended in the US from late 2013 until October 2015, when the FDA began granting approvals for specific carrier status and genetic risk reports.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Products including both ancestry and health-related components have been available in Canada since October 2014 and in the UK since December 2014.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe went public in 2021 through a merger with a special-purpose acquisition company (SPAC), reaching a peak market capitalisation of approximately US$6 billion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] By 2024, its valuation had fallen to roughly 2% of that peak.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In March 2025, the company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy and CEO Anne Wojcicki resigned.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The attorney general of California issued a consumer alert due to privacy concerns surrounding the sensitive genetic data held by the company.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Following a contested bankruptcy auction, TTAM Research Institute—a nonprofit public benefit corporation founded by Wojcicki—outbid Regeneron Pharmaceuticals and acquired substantially all of 23andMe's assets for $305 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] TTAM completed the purchase on July 14, 2025, and the company continues to operate as a nonprofit under TTAM's ownership.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] As of February 2024, 23andMe had genotyped more than 14 million individuals, and its research database has contributed to hundreds of peer-reviewed publications across areas including Parkinson's disease, depression, COVID-19, autoimmune diseases, and pharmacogenomics.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Linda Avey, Paul Cusenza, and Anne Wojcicki founded 23andMe in 2006 to offer genetic testing and interpretation to individuals.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Investment documents from 2007 suggest that 23andMe also intended to develop a database for research purposes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2007, Google invested $3.9 million in the company, along with Genentech, New Enterprise Associates, and Mohr Davidow Ventures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Wojcicki and Google co-founder Sergey Brin were married at the time.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Cusenza left the company in 2007 and Avey departed in 2009.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2012, 23andMe raised $50 million in a Series D venture round, nearly doubling its total capital of $52.6 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2015, a $115 million Series E round brought total capital to $241 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] By late 2017, the company had raised approximately $250 million at a $1.75 billion valuation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] On July 25, 2018, 23andMe announced a partnership with GlaxoSmithKline (GSK) in which GSK would use data from consenting customers to support drug development, investing $300 million in the company.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In January 2022, the partnership was extended until July 2023 with an additional $50 million payment.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In July 2020, the partnership produced its first clinical trial: a jointly developed cancer therapy.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The company was based in Mountain View, California, initially in North Bayshore and then downtown, until 2019, when it moved to larger headquarters in Sunnyvale.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In January 2020, 23andMe laid off about 100 employees in its consumer testing division.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In December 2020, the company raised approximately $82.5 million in a Series F round, bringing total funding to over $850 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In February 2021, 23andMe announced a merger with Sir Richard Branson's special-purpose acquisition company, VG Acquisition Corp, in a $3.5 billion transaction.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The merger closed in June 2021; the combined entity, renamed 23andMe Holding Co., began trading on the Nasdaq under the ticker symbol "ME".
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In October 2021, 23andMe acquired Lemonaid Health, a telehealth company, for $400 million, with the deal closing in November.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] After reaching a market capitalisation of approximately $6 billion following its public listing, 23andMe's valuation fell sharply; by early 2024 it stood at roughly 2% of its peak.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Contributing factors included the company's persistent lack of profitability and the absence of recurring revenue from its one-time DNA test kits.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Wojcicki made several attempts to take the company private.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] An initial bid of $2.53 per share in February 2024 did not proceed.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In July 2024, she offered 40 cents per share for all outstanding shares not already owned by her, but a special committee of the board rejected the proposal.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In September 2024, all seven independent board members resigned.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The company subsequently filed with the SEC indicating it was no longer open to third-party acquisition offers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Users attempting to delete their genetic data discovered that the company retained it for three years to comply with legal obligations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Further layoffs followed in November 2024.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In January 2025, 23andMe disclosed it needed additional liquidity and was exploring strategic alternatives including a potential sale.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Wojcicki made a third offer of 41 cents per share in March 2025.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] On March 23, 2025, 23andMe filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection as part of a plan to sell its assets, listing assets and liabilities each between $100 million and $500 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Wojcicki stepped down as CEO and was replaced by CFO Joe Selsavage.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Trading in the company's shares was suspended on March 31 and the stock was delisted from Nasdaq, subsequently trading over-the-counter.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] California Attorney General Rob Bonta issued a consumer privacy alert reminding Californian users of their right to request deletion of their genetic data.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The initial bankruptcy auction was won by Regeneron Pharmaceuticals for $256 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] As part of that agreement, Regeneron would have acquired all units of 23andMe except its telehealth service Lemonaid Health.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] However, the bankruptcy court reopened the auction after Wojcicki argued that her nonprofit, TTAM Research Institute, had been unfairly excluded from the bidding process.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In the final round, TTAM submitted a winning bid of $305 million.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe had separately announced it would cease being a public company and deregister from the SEC effective June 6, 2025.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] TTAM completed the acquisition of substantially all of 23andMe's assets—including the Personal Genome Service, Research Services, and Lemonaid Health—on July 14, 2025.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] TTAM committed to honouring 23andMe's existing privacy policies, establishing a Consumer Privacy Advisory Board, and restricting future sale or transfer of genetic data unless any new owner adopted equivalent privacy protections.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe began offering direct-to-consumer genetic testing in November 2007.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Customers submit a saliva sample from which DNA is extracted and amplified.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The amplified DNA is applied to a glass microarray chip manufactured by Illumina, which contains microscopic beads, each bearing a gene probe complementary to a specific genetic variant.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Where the customer's DNA matches a probe, the sequences hybridise and a fluorescent label indicates the variant is present.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The platform tests hundreds of thousands of variants out of the approximately 10 to 30 million present in the human genome, and the results are compiled into reports informing the customer about variants associated with conditions such as Parkinson's disease, celiac disease, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2008, when the company was offering estimates of predisposition for more than 90 traits and conditions, *Time* magazine named the product "Invention of the Year".
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Customers can download their uninterpreted raw genetic data and view results by chromosome, including mitochondrial DNA, to compare their variants with common population frequencies.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Ancestry customers have access to genealogical DNA test tools, including a relative-matching database, and can view their mitochondrial haplogroup (maternal lineage) and, if male or if a patrilineal relative has been tested, their Y chromosome haplogroup (paternal lineage).
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] US customers who received health-related results before November 22, 2013, retain online access to assessments of inherited traits and genetic disorder risks.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Health-related results for US customers who purchased the test from November 22, 2013, were suspended until late 2015 while undergoing FDA regulatory review.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Customers in Canada and the United Kingdom have access to some, but not all, health-related results.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe is commonly used by donor-conceived people to find biological siblings and, in some cases, their sperm donor or egg donor.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Until 2010, Illumina sold its genotyping instruments labelled "for research use only"; in early 2010, Illumina obtained FDA approval for its BeadXpress system for clinical use.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In late 2009, 23andMe briefly split its service into three products—an Ancestry Edition, a Health Edition, and a Complete Edition—but recombined them a year later.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] A monthly subscription for research-based updates, introduced in late 2010, proved unpopular and was eliminated in mid-2012.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] From November 22, 2013, to October 21, 2015, 23andMe sold only raw genetic data and ancestry-related results in the US due to FDA restrictions, after which it resumed providing health information in the form of carrier status and wellness reports.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The US price declined from $999 at launch in 2007 to $399 in 2008 and to $99 in 2012, effectively serving as a loss leader to build the customer database.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In October 2015, the price was raised to $199.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In September 2016, an ancestry-only version was reintroduced at $99 with an optional $125 health upgrade.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The product launched in Canada in October 2014 at CA$99 and in the United Kingdom in December 2014 at £125.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In February 2018, 23andMe enhanced its ancestry reporting to provide country-level rather than region-level estimates, adding 120 new regions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Acknowledging gaps in genomic data for Asia and Africa, the company launched the African Genetics Program in October 2016 (supported by a National Institutes of Health grant) to recruit sub-Saharan African participants.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] This was expanded into the Global Genetics Program in February 2018, targeting 61 underrepresented countries, and the Populations Collaboration Program in April 2018, establishing formal research partnerships.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In October 2020, 23andMe launched "23andMe+", a subscription service priced at $29 per year, offering additional health and pharmacogenetic reports to Health + Ancestry customers genotyped on version 5 of its microarray chip.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In late 2021, the company completed its $400 million acquisition of Lemonaid Health, a telehealth company.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The emergence of direct-to-consumer genetic testing raised questions about whether results could be meaningfully interpreted and whether they might lead to genetic discrimination.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The regulatory environment for genetic testing companies remained uncertain, with anticipated risk-based frameworks slow to materialise.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2008, New York and California each notified 23andMe and similar companies that they required CLIA licences to sell tests in those states.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] By August 2008, 23andMe had obtained the necessary California licences.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] According to Wojcicki, 23andMe had been in dialogue with the FDA since 2008.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2010, the FDA notified several genetic testing companies, including 23andMe, that their tests were considered medical devices requiring federal approval; a similar letter was sent to Illumina, which makes the instruments and chips used by 23andMe.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe first submitted applications for FDA clearance in July and September 2012.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In November 2013, the FDA published guidance on how it classified genetic testing services.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] By early December 2013, 23andMe had stopped advertisements for the PGS test and on December 5 suspended health-related results for new customers, continuing to sell ancestry services and raw genetic data.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe publicly acknowledged it had not met the FDA's expectations regarding communication and timelines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Wojcicki described the situation as "new territory for both 23andMe and the FDA", noting that the regulatory process would help establish frameworks for the broader industry.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In May 2014, 23andMe began exploring international markets, including Canada, Australia, and the United Kingdom, to offer its full testing service.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Health-inclusive products launched in Canada in October 2014 and in the United Kingdom in December 2014.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2014, 23andMe submitted a 510(k) application to market a carrier test for Bloom syndrome, providing data on analytical consistency, usability, and clinical validity.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The FDA cleared the test in February 2015, stating it would not require similar applications for other 23andMe carrier tests.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Further clarification was sent on October 1, 2015, and on October 21, 2015, 23andMe resumed marketing carrier tests in the US.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Wojcicki acknowledged that "there was part of us that didn't understand how the regulatory environment works" regarding the distributed roles of the FDA and CMS.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe then submitted "de novo" applications for genetic health risk tests.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The FDA stated it intended to exempt further 23andMe risk tests from 510(k) requirements and clarified that these were risk assessments, not diagnostic tests.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In March 2018, the FDA approved a direct-to-consumer test for three specific *BRCA* mutations most common among people of Ashkenazi descent; these are not the most common *BRCA* mutations in the general population, and the test covers only three of approximately 1,000 known mutations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] These mutations are associated with increased risk of breast and ovarian cancer in women, and breast and prostate cancer in men.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Over 80% of 23andMe customers have opted in to having their data used for research.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The company's research programme has produced hundreds of peer-reviewed publications using its large genotyped and phenotyped participant database.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Aggregated customer data is studied by researchers employed by 23andMe and through collaborations with academic, government, and pharmaceutical partners; de-identified customer data has also been licensed to pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In July 2012, 23andMe acquired CureTogether, a crowdsourced treatment ratings startup with data on over 600 medical conditions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe offers an optional consent allowing individual genetic information to be included in research published in scientific journals.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] However, even without this consent, de-identified genetic and self-reported data may be shared with the company's third-party service providers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2010, 23andMe reported using its database to validate NIH-published work identifying mutations in the glucocerebrosidase gene as a risk factor for Parkinson's disease.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2015, the company began pursuing in-house drug discovery under former Genentech executive Richard Scheller, with Parkinson's disease as a primary focus.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe established research agreements with Pfizer to investigate the genetic basis of inflammatory bowel disease, including ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2016, 23andMe used self-reported customer data to identify 17 genetic loci associated with depression.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2017, the company began collaborations with Lundbeck and the Milken Institute focusing on the genetics of bipolar disorder and major depression, with aims of advancing drug discovery.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In June 2020, 23andMe published preliminary results suggesting that people with type O blood may be at lower risk of COVID-19 infection.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Among more than 750,000 participants, those with type O blood were 9–18% less likely to contract the virus, and those who had been exposed were 13–26% less likely to test positive.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The study was published in April 2021 in *Nature Genetics*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Subsequent research examined genetic associations with COVID-19 symptoms such as loss of taste or smell, vaccine reactions across different ethnicities, and risk factors for long COVID.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Findings on long COVID were presented at the 2023 ASHG conference.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2026, the 23andMe Research Institute published a genome-wide association study in *Nature* identifying genetic variants associated with variation in weight loss and side effects among users of GLP-1 receptor agonist medications.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In 2016, a project to offer customers next-generation sequencing was ended; Wojcicki cited concerns that results would be too complex for direct-to-consumer presentation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Questions have been raised since at least 2013 about whether the company can adequately obtain informed consent through web-based interactions with people submitting samples for genotyping.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The company collects not only genetic and personal information from customers but also web behaviour data through its website, apps, cookies, and software.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] People may not be aware of how the company uses their data, and there are inherent risks of data breaches.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Personal information of customers "may be accessed, sold or transferred".
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Since 23andMe is not classified as a medical provider, it is not subject to the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA).
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Research has found that very few consumers read terms and conditions (9% according to Deloitte; 1% according to ProPrivacy), suggesting many customers may have consented to research participation without fully understanding the permissions granted.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe's privacy policy has been described as confusing for consumers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Despite these concerns, 23andMe's informed consent practices have been approved by an institutional review board.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) protects individuals against discrimination based on genetic information by employers and health insurers in most situations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] However, GINA does not extend to life insurance, long-term care, or disability insurance providers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Effective May 25, 2018, 23andMe became subject to the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which governs the collection, use, and storage of personal data and applies to companies offering services to individuals in the European Union, regardless of where the company is based.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] 23andMe's transparency report, as of September 2024, states that the company had received requests from law enforcement for 15 US users' data since 2015, with none from other countries.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] No data was produced in response to any of these requests.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The privacy policy states that 23andMe will not voluntarily share personal information with law enforcement absent a valid court order, subpoena, or search warrant.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In October 2023, a significant data breach was disclosed.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Hackers accessed data on approximately 6.9 million users—roughly half of 23andMe's customers at the time—through a credential stuffing attack.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] Stolen data included names, addresses, and genetic information, and was subsequently offered for sale online.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] The affected accounts had enabled the platform's "DNA Relatives" feature, and the attack specifically targeted Ashkenazi Jewish and Chinese-descent users.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In June 2025, the UK's Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) fined 23andMe £2.31 million for failing to adequately protect user data, citing inadequate security measures—including the absence of multi-factor authentication—and a slow response to the breach.
[src:austronesian-peoples/23andme] In May 2026, the California Attorney General filed a lawsuit against 23andMe for failure to safeguard sensitive personal information under the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) and other related privacy statutes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] 'alphabet') is a writing system in which only consonants are represented by letter signs, leaving the vowels to be inferred by the reader (unless represented otherwise, such as by diacritics).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] This contrasts with alphabets that provide graphemes for both consonants and vowels.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The term was introduced in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Other terms for the same concept include **partial phonemic script**, **segmentally linear defective phonographic script**, **consonantary**, **consonant writing**, and **consonantal alphabet**.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] According to the formulations of Peter T.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Daniels, abjads differ from alphabets in that only consonants, not vowels, are represented among the basic graphemes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Abjads differ from abugidas, another category defined by Daniels, in that in abjads, the vowel sound is *implied* by phonology, and where vowel marks exist for the system, such as niqqud for Hebrew and ḥarakāt for Arabic, their use is optional and not the dominant (or literate) form.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Abugidas mark all vowels (other than the "inherent" vowel) with a diacritic, a minor attachment to the letter, a standalone grapheme, or (in Canadian Aboriginal syllabics) by rotation of the letter.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Some abugidas use a special symbol to *suppress* the inherent vowel so that the consonant alone can be properly represented.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] In a syllabary, a grapheme denotes a complete syllable, that is, either a lone vowel sound or a combination of a vowel sound with one or more consonant sounds.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The contrast of abjad versus alphabet has been rejected by other scholars because *abjad* is also used as a term for the Arabic numeral system.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Also, it may be taken as suggesting that consonantal alphabets, in contrast to e.g. the Greek alphabet, were not yet true alphabets.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Florian Coulmas, a critic of Daniels and of the abjad terminology, argues that this terminology can confuse alphabets with "transcription systems", and that there is no reason to relegate the Hebrew, Aramaic or Phoenician alphabets to second-class status as an "incomplete alphabet".
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] However, Daniels's terminology has found acceptance in the linguistic community.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script represents the earliest-known example of alphabetic writing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script is thought to represent, or at least indicate the existence of, an early ancestor of the many later Semitic consonantal scripts which continued to develop over time into more abstract, less visually representational forms, including the Phoenician abjad.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The Phoenician abjad was a radical simplification of phonetic writing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Unlike other scripts, such as Mesopotamian cuneiform (logographic and syllabic) and Egyptian hieroglyphs (logographic and consonantal), the Phoenician abjad consisted of only a few dozen symbols.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] During these exchanges, the Phoenician script gave rise to a number of new writing systems, including the widely used Aramaic abjad and the Greek alphabet.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The Greek alphabet was later developed into several alphabets, including Etruscan, Coptic, Cyrillic, and Latin (via Etruscan), while Aramaic became the ancestor of many abjads and abugidas of Asia, particularly in and around India, Southeast Asia, and Oceania.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Impure abjads have characters for some vowels, optional vowel diacritics, or both.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The term pure abjad refers to scripts entirely lacking in vowel indicators.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] This practice was at first rare and limited in scope but became increasingly common and more developed in later times.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] In the 9th century BC the Greeks adapted the Phoenician script for use in their own language.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The phonetic structure of the Greek language created too many ambiguities when vowels went unrepresented, so the script was modified.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] They did not need letters for the guttural sounds represented by *aleph*, *he*, *heth* or *ayin*, so these symbols were assigned vocalic values.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The letters *waw* and *yod* were also adapted into vowel signs; along with *he*, these were already used as *matres lectionis* in Phoenician.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Abugidas developed along a slightly different route.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The basic consonantal symbol was considered to have an inherent "a" vowel sound.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Hooks or short lines attached to various parts of the basic letter modify the vowel.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] In this way, the South Arabian abjad evolved into the Geʽez script of Ethiopia between the 5th century BC and the 5th century AD.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] Similarly, the Brāhmī abugida of the Indian subcontinent developed around the 3rd century BC (from the Aramaic abjad, it has been hypothesized).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The abjad form of writing is well-adapted to the morphological structure of the Semitic languages it was developed to write.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] This is because words in Semitic languages are formed from a root consisting of (usually) three consonants, the vowels being used to indicate inflectional or derived forms.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] In most cases, the absence of full glyphs for vowels makes the common root clearer, allowing readers to guess the meaning of unfamiliar words from familiar roots (especially in conjunction with context clues) and improving word recognition while reading for practiced readers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abjad] The Hebrew abjad has also been adapted to write Jewish languages like Ladino and Yiddish.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:austronesian-peoples/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They also include indigenous ethnic minorities in Vietnam, Cambodia, Myanmar, Thailand, Hainan, and the Torres Strait Islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The nations and territories predominantly populated by Austronesian-speaking peoples are sometimes known collectively as **Austronesia**.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The group originated from a prehistoric seaborne migration, known as the Austronesian expansion, from Taiwan, circa 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians reached the Batanes Islands in the northernmost Philippines by around 2200 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They used sails some time before 2000 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In conjunction with their use of other maritime technologies (notably catamarans, outrigger boats, lashed-lug boats, and the crab claw sail), this enabled phases of rapid dispersal into the islands of the Indo-Pacific, culminating in the settlement of New Zealand c.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] During the initial part of the migrations, they encountered and assimilated (or were assimilated by) the Paleolithic populations that had migrated earlier into Maritime Southeast Asia and New Guinea.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They reached as far as Easter Island to the east, Madagascar to the west, and New Zealand to the south.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] At the furthest extent, they might have also reached the Americas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Aside from language, Austronesian peoples widely share cultural characteristics, including such traditions and traditional technologies as lashed-lug shipbuilding, tattooing, stilt houses, jade carving, wetland agriculture, and various rock art motifs.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They also share domesticated plants and animals that were carried along with the migrations, including rice, bananas, coconuts, breadfruit, *Dioscorea* yams, taro, paper mulberry, chickens, pigs, and dogs.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The linguistic connections between Madagascar, Polynesia, and Southeast Asia, particularly the similarities between Malagasy, Malay, and Polynesian numerals, were recognized early in the colonial era by European authors.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] German naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster, who traveled with James Cook on his second voyage, also recognized the similarities of Polynesian languages to those of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In his book *Observations Made during a Voyage round the World* (1778), he posited that the ultimate origins of the Polynesians might have been the lowland regions of the Philippines and proposed that they arrived to the islands via long-distance voyaging.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Multiple other authors corroborated this classification (except for the erroneous inclusion of Maldivian), and the language family came to be known as "Malayo-Polynesian", first coined by the German linguist Franz Bopp in 1841 (German: *malayisch-polynesisch*).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The connections between Southeast Asia, Madagascar, and the Pacific Islands were also noted by other European explorers, including the Orientalist William Marsden and the naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Johann Friedrich Blumenbach added Austronesians as the fifth category to his "varieties" of humans in the second edition of *De Generis Humani Varietate Nativa* (1781).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] He initially grouped them by geography and thus called Austronesians the "people from the southern world".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In the third edition, published in 1795, he named Austronesians the "Malay race", or the "brown race", after correspondence with Joseph Banks, who was part of the first voyage of James Cook.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Blumenbach used the term "Malay" due to his belief that most Austronesians spoke the "Malay idiom" (i.e., the Austronesian languages), though he inadvertently caused the later confusion of his racial category with the Malay ethnic group.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The other varieties Blumenbach identified were the "Caucasians" (white), "Mongolians" (yellow), "Ethiopians" (black), and "Americans" (red).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Blumenbach's definition of the "Malay" race is largely identical to the modern distribution of the Austronesian peoples, including not only Islander Southeast Asians but also the people of Madagascar and the Pacific Islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Although Blumenbach's work was later used in scientific racism, Blumenbach was a monogenist and did not believe the human "varieties" were inherently inferior to each other.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Rather, he believed that the Malay race was a combination of the "Ethiopian" and "Caucasian" varieties.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] — Johann Friedrich Blumenbach,*The anthropological treatises of Johann Friedrich Blumenbach*, translated by Thomas Bendyshe, 1865.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] By the 19th century, however, a classification of Austronesians as being a subset of the "Mongolian" race was favored, as was polygenism.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The British naturalist James Cowles Prichard originally followed Blumenbach by treating Papuans and Indigenous Australians as being descendants of the same stock as Austronesians.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] But by his third edition of *Researches into the Physical History of Man* (1836–1847), his work had become more racialized due to the influence of polygenism.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] He classified the peoples of Austronesia into two groups: the "Malayo-Polynesians" (roughly equivalent to the Austronesian peoples) and the "Kelænonesians" (roughly equivalent to the Australo-Melanesians).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] He further subdivided the latter into the "Alfourous" (also "Haraforas" or "Alfoërs", the Native Australians), and the "Pelagian or Oceanic Negroes" (the Melanesians and western Polynesians).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Despite this, he acknowledges that "Malayo-Polynesians" and "Pelagian Negroes" had "remarkable characters in common", particularly in terms of language and craniometry.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In linguistics, the Malayo-Polynesian language family also initially excluded Melanesia and Micronesia, due to the perceived physical differences between the inhabitants of these regions from Malayo-Polynesian speakers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, there was growing evidence of their linguistic relationship to Malayo-Polynesian languages, notably from studies on the Melanesian languages by Georg von der Gabelentz, Robert Henry Codrington, and Sidney Herbert Ray.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Codrington coined and used the term "Ocean" language family rather than "Malayo-Polynesian" in 1891, in opposition to the exclusion of Melanesian and Micronesian languages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This was adopted by Ray, who defined the "Oceanic" language family as encompassing the languages of Southeast Asia and Madagascar, Micronesia, Melanesia, and Polynesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In 1899, the Austrian linguist and ethnologist Wilhelm Schmidt coined the term "Austronesian" (German: *austronesisch*, from Latin *auster*, "south wind"; and Greek *νῆσος*, "island") to refer to the language family.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Schmidt had the same motivations as Codrington: he proposed the term as a replacement to "Malayo-Polynesian", because he also opposed the implied exclusion of the languages of Melanesia and Micronesia in the latter name.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] It became the accepted name for the language family, with Oceanic and Malayo-Polynesian languages being retained as names for subgroups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The term "Austronesian", or more accurately "Austronesian-speaking peoples", came to refer to people who speak the languages of the Austronesian language family.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some authors, however, object to the use of the term to refer to people, as they question whether there really is any biological or cultural shared ancestry between all Austronesian-speaking groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This is especially true for authors who reject the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis and instead offer scenarios where the Austronesian languages spread among preexisting static populations through borrowing or convergence, with little or no population movements.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Despite these objections, the general consensus is that the archeological, cultural, genetic, and especially linguistic evidence all separately indicate varying degrees of shared ancestry among Austronesian-speaking peoples that justifies their treatment as a "phylogenetic unit".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This has led to the use of the term "Austronesian" in academic literature to refer not only to the Austronesian languages but also the Austronesian-speaking peoples, their societies, and the geographic area of Austronesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some Austronesian-speaking groups are not direct descendants of Austronesians and acquired their languages through language shift, but this is believed to have happened only in a few instances, since the Austronesian expansion was too rapid for language shifts to have occurred fast enough.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In parts of Island Melanesia, migrations and paternal admixture from Papuan groups after the Austronesian expansion (estimated to have started at around 500 BCE) also resulted in gradual population turnover.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These secondary migrations were incremental and happened gradually enough that the culture and language of these groups remained Austronesian, even though in modern times, they are genetically more Papuan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In the vast majority of cases, the language and material culture of Austronesian-speaking groups descend directly through generational continuity, especially in islands that were previously uninhabited.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Serious research into the Austronesian languages and its speakers has been ongoing since the 19th century.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Modern scholarship on Austronesian dispersion models is generally credited to two influential papers in the late 20th century: *The Colonization of the Pacific: A Genetic Trail* (Hill & Serjeantson, eds., 1989) and *The Austronesian Dispersal and the Origin of Languages* (Bellwood, 1991).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The topic is particularly interesting to scientists for the remarkably unique characteristics of the Austronesian speakers: their extent, diversity, and rapid dispersal.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Regardless, certain disagreements still exist among researchers with regards to chronology, origin, dispersal, adaptations to the island environments, interactions with preexisting populations in areas they settled, and cultural developments over time.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The mainstream accepted hypothesis is the "Out of Taiwan" model first proposed by Peter Bellwood.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] But there are multiple rival models that create a sort of "pseudo-competition" among their supporters due to narrow focus on data from limited geographic areas or disciplines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The most notable of which is the "Out of Sundaland" (or "Out of Island Southeast Asia") model.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians were the first humans with seafaring vessels that could cross large distances on the open ocean; this technology allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Prior to the 16th-century colonial era, the Austronesian language family was the most widespread in the world, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Languages of the Austronesian family are today spoken by about 386 million people (4.9% of the global population), making it the fifth-largest language family by number of speakers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Major Austronesian languages include Malay (around 250–270 million in Indonesia alone in its own literary standard, named Indonesian), Javanese, and Filipino (Tagalog).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The family contains 1,257 languages, the second-largest number of any language family.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The geographic region that encompasses native Austronesian-speaking populations is sometimes referred to as "Austronesia".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In Indonesia, the nationalistic term Nusantara, from Old Javanese, is also popularly used for the Indonesian islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesian regions are almost exclusively islands in the Pacific and Indian oceans, with predominantly tropical or subtropical climates with considerable seasonal rainfall.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Inhabitants of these regions include Taiwanese indigenous peoples, most ethnic groups in Brunei, East Timor, Indonesia, Madagascar, Malaysia, Micronesia, the Philippines, and Polynesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Also included are the Malays of Singapore; the Polynesians of New Zealand, Hawaii, and Chile; the Torres Strait Islanders of Australia; the non-Papuan peoples of Melanesia and coastal New Guinea; the Shibushi speakers of Mayotte, and the Malagasy and Shibushi speakers of Réunion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians are also found in the regions of Southern Thailand; the Cham areas in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Hainan; and the Mergui Archipelago of Myanmar.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Additionally, modern-era migration has brought Austronesian-speaking people to the United States, Canada, Australia, the UK, mainland Europe, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Suriname, Hong Kong, Macau, and West Asian countries.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some authors also propose further settlements and contacts in the past in areas that are not inhabited by Austronesian speakers today.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These range from likely hypotheses to very controversial claims with minimal evidence.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In 2009, Roger Blench compiled an expanded map of Austronesia that encompassed these claims based on a variety of evidence, such as historical accounts, loanwords, introduced plants and animals, genetics, archeological sites, and material culture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They include areas like the Pacific coast of the Americas, Japan, the Yaeyama Islands, the Australian coast, Sri Lanka and coastal South Asia, the Persian Gulf, some Indian Ocean islands, East Africa, South Africa, and West Africa.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians also mixed with other preexisting populations as well as later migrant populations among the islands they settled, resulting in further genetic input.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The most notable are the Austroasiatic-speaking peoples in western Island Southeast Asia (peninsular Malaysia, Sumatra, Borneo, and Java); the Bantu peoples in Madagascar; as well as Japanese, Persian, Indian, Arab, and Han Chinese traders and migrants in more recent centuries.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Island Southeast Asia was settled by modern humans in the Paleolithic following coastal migration routes, presumably starting before 70,000 BP from Africa, long before the development of Austronesian cultures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These populations are typified by having dark skin, curly hair, and short statures, leading Europeans to believe, in the 19th century, that they were related to African Pygmies.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, despite these physical similarities, genetic studies have shown that they are more closely related to other Eurasian populations than to Africans.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The lowered sea levels of the Pleistocene made some of the modern-day islands of Sundaland accessible via land bridges.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, the spread of humans across the Wallace line and into Sahul necessitated crossing bodies of water.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Remains of stone tools and marine shells in Liang Sarru, Salibabu Island, North Sulawesi, dated to 32,000–35,000 years ago, is possible evidence for the longest sea voyage by Paleolithic humans ever recorded.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The island was previously uninhabited by humans or hominins and can only be reached from either Mindanao or the Sangihe Islands by crossing an expanse of water at least 100 km (62 mi) wide, even during the low sea levels of the Pleistocene.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Other evidence of early maritime transport are the appearance of obsidian tools with the same source on neighboring islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These include the Philippine obsidian network (Mindoro and Palawan, ca.33,000-28,000 BP), and the Wallacea obsidian network (Timor, Atauro, Kisar, Alor, ca.22,000 BP).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, the method of crossing remains unknown and could have ranged from simple rafts to dugout canoes by the terminal Pleistocene.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These early settlers are generally historically referred to as "Australo-Melanesians", though the terminology is problematic, as they are genetically diverse, and most groups within Austronesia have significant Austronesian admixture and culture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The unmixed descendants of these groups today include the interior Papuans and Indigenous Australians.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In modern literature, descendants of these groups, located in Island Southeast Asia west of Halmahera, are usually collectively referred to as "Negritos", while descendants of these groups east of Halmahera (excluding Indigenous Australians) are referred to as "Papuans".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They can also be divided into two broad groups based on Denisovan admixture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Philippine Negritos, Papuans, Melanesians, and Indigenous Australians display Denisovan admixture, while Malaysian and western Indonesian Negritos (Orang Asli) and Andamanese islanders do not.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Mahdi (2017) also uses the term "Qata" (from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *qata) to distinguish the indigenous populations of Southeast Asia, versus "Tau" (from Proto-Austronesian *Cau) for the later settlers from Taiwan and mainland China.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Both are based on proto-forms for the word "person" in Malayo-Polynesian languages that referred to darker-skinned and lighter-skinned groups, respectively.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Jinam *et al.* (2017) also proposed the term "First Sundaland People" in place of "Negrito", as a more accurate name for the original population of Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These populations are genetically distinct from later Austronesians, but through fairly extensive population admixture, most modern Austronesians have varying levels of ancestry from these groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The same is true for some populations historically considered "non-Austronesians", due to physical differences—like Philippine Negritos, Orang Asli, and Austronesian-speaking Melanesians, all of whom have Austronesian admixture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In Polynesians in Remote Oceania, for example, the admixture is around 20 to 30% Papuan and 70 to 80% Austronesian.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Melanesians in Near Oceania are roughly around 20% Austronesian and 80% Papuan, while in the natives of the Lesser Sunda Islands, the admixture is around 50% Austronesian and 50% Papuan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Similarly, in the Philippines, the groups traditionally considered to be "Negrito" vary between 30 and 50% Austronesian.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The high degree of assimilation among Austronesian, Negrito, and Papuan groups indicates that the Austronesian expansion was largely peaceful.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Rather than violent displacement, the settlers and the indigenous groups absorbed each other.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] It is believed that in some cases, like in the Toalean culture of Sulawesi (c.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] 8,000–1,500 BP), it is even more accurate to say that the densely populated indigenous hunter-gatherer groups absorbed the incoming Austronesian farmers, rather than the other way around.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Mahdi (2016) further asserts that Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *tau-mata ("person") is derived from a composite protoform *Cau ma-qata, combining "Tau" and "Qata" and indicative of the mixing of the two ancestral population types in these regions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The broad consensus on the Urheimat (homeland) of Austronesian languages as well as the Neolithic early Austronesian peoples is accepted to be Taiwan, as well as the Penghu Islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They are believed to have descended from ancestral populations in coastal mainland southern China, which are generally referred to as the "pre‑Austronesians".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Through these pre-Austronesians, Austronesians may also share a common ancestry with neighboring groups in Neolithic southern China.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These Neolithic pre-Austronesians from the coast of southeastern China are believed to have migrated to Taiwan between approximately 10,000 and 6000 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Other research has suggested that, according to radiocarbon dates, Austronesians may have migrated from mainland China to Taiwan as late as 4000 BCE (Dapenkeng culture).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They continued to maintain regular contact with the mainland until 1500 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The identity of the Neolithic pre-Austronesian cultures in China is contentious.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Tracing Austronesian prehistory in Fujian and Taiwan has been difficult due to the southward expansion of the Han dynasty (2nd century BCE) and the recent Qing dynasty annexation of Taiwan (1683 CE).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Today, the only Austronesian language in southern China is Tsat, spoken in Hainan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The politicization of archaeology is also problematic, particularly erroneous reconstructions among some Chinese archaeologists of non-Sinitic sites as Han.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some authors, favoring the "Out of Sundaland" model, like William Meacham, reject the southern Chinese mainland origin of pre-Austronesians entirely.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Nevertheless, based on linguistic, archaeological, and genetic evidence, Austronesians are most strongly associated with the early farming cultures of the Yangtze River basin that domesticated rice from around 13,500 to 8,200 BP.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They display typical Austronesian technological hallmarks, including tooth removal, teeth blackening, jade carving, tattooing, stilt houses, advanced boatbuilding, aquaculture, wetland agriculture, and the domestication of dogs, pigs, and chickens.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These include the Kuahuqiao, Hemudu, Majiabang, Songze, Liangzhu, and Dapenkeng cultures that occupied the coastal regions between the Yangtze River delta and the Min River delta.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Based on linguistic evidence, there have been proposals linking Austronesians with other linguistic families into linguistic macrofamilies that are relevant to the identity of the pre-Austronesian populations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The most notable are the connections of Austronesians to the neighboring Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Sinitic peoples (as Austric, Austro-Tai, and Sino-Austronesian, respectively).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These are still not widely accepted, as evidence of these relationships are still tenuous, and the methods used are highly contentious.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Under that view, there was an east–west genetic alignment, resulting from a rice-based population expansion, in the southern part of East Asia: Austroasiatic-Kra-Dai-Austronesian, with unrelated Sino-Tibetan occupying a more northerly tier.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Depending on the author, other hypotheses have also included other language families like Hmong–Mien and even Japanese-Ryukyuan into the larger Austric hypothesis.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These peoples were assimilated linguistically and culturally by incoming Austronesian peoples in what is now modern-day Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They propose that the distinctiveness of Kra-Dai (it is tonal and monosyllabic) was the result of linguistic restructuring due to contact with Hmong–Mien and Sinitic cultures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Aside from linguistic evidence, Roger Blench has also noted cultural similarities between the two groups, like facial tattooing, tooth removal or ablation, teeth blackening, snake (or dragon) cults, and the multiple-tongued jaw harps shared by the indigenous Taiwanese and Kra-Dai-speakers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, archaeological evidence for this is still sparse.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This is believed to be similar to what happened to the Cham people, who were originally Austronesian settlers (likely from Borneo) to southern Vietnam around 2100–1900 BP and had languages similar to Malay.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Their languages underwent several restructuring events to syntax and phonology due to contact with the nearby tonal languages of Mainland Southeast Asia and Hainan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Although the populations of the Malay peninsula, Sumatra, Java, and neighboring islands are Austronesian-speaking, they have significantly high admixture from Mainland Southeast Asian populations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These areas were already populated (most probably by speakers of Austroasiatic languages) before they were reached by the Austronesian expansion, roughly 3,000 years ago.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Currently, only the indigenous Aslians still speak Austroasiatic languages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, some of the languages in the region show signs of underlying Austroasiatic substrates.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] According to Juha Janhunen and Ann Kumar, Austronesians may have also settled parts of southern Japan, especially on the islands of Kyushu and Shikoku, and influenced or created the Japanese hierarchical society.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] It is suggested that Japanese tribes like the Hayato people, the Kumaso, and the Azumi were of Austronesian origin.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Until today, local traditions and festivals show similarities to Malayo-Polynesian culture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Sino-Austronesian hypothesis, on the other hand, is a relatively new hypothesis by Laurent Sagart, first proposed in 1990.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] It argues for a north–south linguistic genetic relationship between Chinese and Austronesian.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This is based on sound correspondences in basic vocabulary and morphological parallels.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Sagart places special significance in shared vocabulary on cereal crops, citing them as evidence of shared linguistic origin.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, this has largely been rejected by other linguists.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This corresponded with the widespread introduction of rice cultivation to Proto-Sinitic speakers and conversely, millet cultivation to Pre-Austronesians.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] An Austronesian substratum in formerly Austronesian territories that have been Sinicized after the Iron Age Han expansion is also another explanation for the correspondences that do not require a genetic relationship.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The surviving Austronesian populations in Taiwan should rather be considered as the result of various Neolithic migration waves from the mainland and back-migration from the Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These incoming migrants almost certainly spoke languages related to Austronesian or pre-Austronesian, although their phonology and grammar would have been quite diverse.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Blench considers the Austronesians in Taiwan to have been a melting pot of immigrants from various parts of the coast of East China that had been migrating to Taiwan by 4000 BP.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Based on geography and cultural vocabulary, Blench believes that the Yuanshan people may have spoken Northeast Formosan languages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Thus, Blench believes that there is in fact no "apical" ancestor of Austronesian in the sense that there was no true single Proto-Austronesian language that gave rise to present-day Austronesian languages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Instead, multiple migrations of various pre-Austronesian peoples and languages from the Chinese mainland that were related but distinct came together to form what we now know as Austronesian in Taiwan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Hence, Blench considers the single-migration model into Taiwan by pre-Austronesians to be inconsistent with both the archaeological and linguistic (lexical) evidence.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The **Austronesian expansion** (also called the "Out of Taiwan" model) is a large-scale migration of Austronesians from Taiwan, occurring around 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Population growth primarily fueled this migration.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] These first settlers settled in northern Luzon, in the archipelago of the Philippines, intermingling with the earlier Australo-Melanesian population who had inhabited the islands since about 23,000 years earlier.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Over the next thousand years, Austronesian peoples migrated southeast to the rest of the Philippines, and into the islands of the Celebes Sea and Borneo.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] From southwestern Borneo, Austronesians spread further west in a single migration event to both Sumatra and the coastal regions of southern Vietnam, becoming the ancestors of the speakers of the Malayic and Chamic branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] A 2021 study, however, suggests an earlier divergence date between Cordilleran-related groups and populations from mainland East Asia and Taiwan at ~8,000 B.P., coinciding with the Cordilleran settlement of the Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Soon after reaching the Philippines, Austronesians colonized the Northern Mariana Islands by 1500 BCE or even earlier, becoming the first humans to reach Remote Oceania.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Chamorro migration was also unique in that it was the only Austronesian migration to the Pacific Islands to successfully retain rice cultivation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Palau and Yap were settled by separate voyages by 1000 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Another important migration branch was by the Lapita culture, which rapidly spread into the islands off the coast of northern New Guinea and into the Solomon Islands and other parts of coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia by 1200 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They reached the islands of Fiji, Samoa, and Tonga by around 900 to 800 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This remained the furthest extent of the Austronesian expansion into Polynesia until around 700 CE, when there was another surge of island colonization.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] It reached the Cook Islands, Tahiti, and the Marquesas by 700 CE; Hawaii by 900 CE; Rapa Nui by 1000 CE; and New Zealand by 1200 CE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] For a few centuries, the Polynesian islands were connected by bidirectional long-distance sailing, with the exception of Rapa Nui, which had limited further contact due to its isolated geographical location.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Island groups like the Pitcairns, the Kermadec Islands, and the Norfolk Islands were also formerly settled by Austronesians but later abandoned.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] There is also putative evidence, based in the spread of the sweet potato, that Austronesians may have reached South America from Polynesia, where they might have traded with the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] In the Indian Ocean, Austronesians in Maritime Southeast Asia established trade links with South Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] They also established early long-distance contacts with Africa, possibly as early as before 500 BCE, based on archaeological evidence like banana phytoliths in Cameroon and Uganda and remains of Neolithic chicken bones in Zanzibar.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] By the end of the first millennium BCE, Austronesians were already sailing maritime trade routes linking the Han dynasty of China with the western Indian Ocean trade in India, the Roman Empire, and Africa.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] An Austronesian group, originally from the Makassar Strait region around Kalimantan and Sulawesi, eventually settled Madagascar, either directly from Southeast Asia or from preexisting mixed Austronesian-Bantu populations from East Africa.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Estimates for when this occurred vary, from the 5th to 7th centuries CE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] It is likely that the Austronesians that settled Madagascar followed a coastal route through South Asia and East Africa, rather than directly across the Indian Ocean.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Genetic evidence suggests that some individuals of Austronesian descent reached Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] A competing hypothesis to the "Out of Taiwan" model is the "Out of Sundaland" hypothesis, favored by a minority of authors.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Notable proponents include William Meacham, Stephen Oppenheimer, and Wilhelm Solheim.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] For various reasons, they have proposed that the homelands of Austronesians were within Island Southeast Asia (ISEA), particularly in the Sundaland landmass drowned during the end of the Last Glacial Period by rising sea levels.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Proponents of these hypotheses point to the ancient origins of mtDNA in Southeast Asian populations, pre-dating the Austronesian expansion, as proof that Austronesians originated from within Island Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, these have been repudiated by studies using whole genome sequencing, which have found that all ISEA populations had genes originating from aboriginal Taiwanese.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Contrary to the claim of a south-to-north migration in the "Out of Sundaland" hypothesis, the new whole genome analysis strongly confirms the north-to-south dispersal of the Austronesian peoples in the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Researchers have further pointed out that while humans have been living in Sundaland for at least 40,000 years, the Austronesian people were recent arrivals.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The results of the previous studies failed to take into account admixture with the more ancient but unrelated Negrito and Papuan populations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] By the beginning of the first millennium CE, most of the Austronesian inhabitants in Maritime Southeast Asia began trading with India and China.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The adoption of the Hindu statecraft model allowed the creation of Indianized kingdoms, such as Tarumanagara, Champa, Butuan, Langkasuka, Melayu, Srivijaya, Mataram, Majapahit, and Bali.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Between the 5th and the 15th century, Hinduism and Buddhism were established as the main religion in the region.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Muslim traders from the Arabian Peninsula were thought to have brought Islam by the 10th century.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] This was established as the dominant religion in the Malay archipelago by the 16th century.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Austronesian inhabitants of Near Oceania and Remote Oceania were unaffected by this cultural trade and retained their indigenous culture in the Pacific region.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Kingdom of Larantuka in Flores, East Nusa Tenggara, was the only Christian (Roman Catholic) indigenous kingdom in Indonesia and in Southeast Asia, with its first king named Lorenzo.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] Meanwhile, the British, Germans, French, Americans, and Japanese began establishing spheres of influence within the Pacific islands during the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Japanese later invaded most of Southeast Asia and some parts of the Pacific during World War II.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p01] The latter half of the 20th century initiated independence of modern-day Indonesia, Malaysia, East Timor, and many of the Pacific island nations, as well as the re-independence of the Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The native culture of Austronesia varies from region to region.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The early Austronesian peoples considered the sea as the basic feature of their life.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Following their diaspora to Southeast Asia and Oceania, they migrated by boat to other islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Boats of different sizes and shapes have been found in every Austronesian culture, from Madagascar, Maritime Southeast Asia, to Polynesia, and have different names.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In Southeast Asia, head-hunting was restricted to the highlands as a result of warfare.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Mummification is only found among the highland Austronesian Filipinos and in some Indonesian groups in Celebes and Borneo.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Seagoing catamaran and outrigger ship technologies were the most important innovations of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They were the first humans with vessels capable of crossing vast distances of water.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The crossing from the Philippines to the Mariana Islands at around 1500 BCE, a distance of more than 2,500 km (1,600 mi), is likely the world's first and longest ocean crossing of that time.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These maritime technologies enabled them to colonize the Indo-Pacific in prehistoric times.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian groups continue to be the primary users of outrigger canoes today.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Early researchers like Heine-Geldern (1932) and Hornell (1943) once believed that catamarans evolved from outrigger canoes, but modern authors specializing in Austronesian cultures, like Doran (1981) and Mahdi (1988), now believe it to be the opposite.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Two canoes bound together developed directly from minimal raft technologies of two logs tied together.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Over time, the double-hulled canoe form developed into the asymmetric double canoe, where one hull is smaller than the other.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Eventually the smaller hull became the prototype outrigger, giving way to the single outrigger canoe, then to the reversible single outrigger canoe.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Finally, the single outrigger types developed into the double outrigger canoe (or trimarans).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This would also explain why older Austronesian populations in Island Southeast Asia tend to favor double outrigger canoes, as it keeps the boats stable when tacking.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] However, there are small regions where catamarans and single-outrigger canoes are still used.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In contrast, more distant outlying descendant populations in Micronesia, Polynesia and Madagascar retained the double-hull and the single-outrigger canoe types, but the technology for double outriggers never reached them (although it exists in western Melanesia).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] To deal with the problem of the boat's instability when the outrigger faces leeward when tacking, they instead developed the shunting technique in sailing, in conjunction with reversible single-outriggers.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The bottom consisted of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge, with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fiber) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibers that would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The ancestral rig was the mastless triangular crab claw sail, which had two booms that could be tilted to the wind.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These were built in the double-canoe configuration or had a single outrigger on the windward side.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In Island Southeast Asia, these developed into double outriggers on each side, which provided greater stability.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The triangular crab claw sails also later developed into square or rectangular tanja sails, which, like crab claw sails, had distinctive booms spanning the upper and lower edges.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Fixed masts also developed later in both Southeast Asia (usually as bipod or tripod masts) and Oceania.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesians traditionally made their sails from woven mats of the resilient and salt-resistant pandanus leaves.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These sails allowed them to embark on long-distance voyaging.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In some cases, however, they were one-way voyages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The motives of early Rapa Nui natives and Māori to establish their settlements (Easter Island and New Zealand) are believed to have isolated their settlements from the rest of Polynesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The ancient Champa of Vietnam also uniquely developed basket-hulled boats whose hulls were composed of woven and resin-caulked bamboo, either entirely or in conjunction with plank strakes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They ranged from small coracles (*o thúng*) to large oceangoing trading ships like the *ghe mành*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The acquisition of catamaran and outrigger technology by non-Austronesian peoples in Sri Lanka and southern India is due to the result of very early Austronesian contact with the region, including the Maldives and the Laccadive Islands, estimated to have occurred around 1000 to 600 BCE and onwards.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This may have possibly included limited colonization by people who have since been assimilated.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This is still evident in Sri Lankan and South Indian languages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian architecture is diverse but often shares certain characteristics that indicate a common origin.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian structures commonly have raised floors.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The structures are raised on piles, usually with space underneath also utilized for storage or domestic animals.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The raised design has multiple advantages, including mitigating damage during flooding and (in very tall examples) acting as defensive structures during conflicts.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The house posts are also distinctively capped with larger-diameter discs at the top, to prevent vermin and pests from entering the structures by climbing them.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian houses and other structures are usually built in wetlands and alongside bodies of water but can also be constructed in the highlands or even directly on shallow water.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Building structures on pilings is believed to be derived from the design of raised granaries and storehouses, which are highly important status symbols among the ancestrally rice-cultivating Austronesians.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The rice granary shrine was also the archetypal religious building among Austronesian cultures and was used to store carvings of ancestor spirits and local deities.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Another common feature are pitched roofs with ornamented gables.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The most notable of these are saddlebacked roofs, a design common for longhouses used for village meetings or ceremonies.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The overall effect of this is reminiscent of a boat, underlining the strong maritime connections of Austronesian cultures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The boat motif is common throughout, particularly in Eastern Indonesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In some ethnic groups, the houses are built on platforms that resemble catamarans.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Among the Nage people, a woven representation of a boat is added to the ridge of the roof; among the Manggarai people, the roofs of houses are shaped like an upside-down boat; while among the people of Tanimbar and eastern Flores, the ridge itself is carved into a representation of a boat.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Furthermore, elements of Austronesian structures (as well as society in general) are often referred to in terminologies used for boats and sailing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These include calling elements of structures "masts", "sails", or "rudders", or calling the village leaders "captains" or "steersmen".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In the case of the Philippines, the villages themselves are referred to as *barangay*, from an alternate form of *balangay*, a type of sailboat used for trading and colonization.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian buildings have spiritual significance, often containing what has been coined by anthropologist James J.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These are specific posts, beams, platforms, altars, and so on that embody the house as a whole, usually consecrated at the time of building.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The Austronesian house itself also often symbolizes various aspects of indigenous Austronesian cosmology and animism.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In the majority of cases, the loft of the house (usually placed above the hearth), is considered to be the domain of deities and spirits.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] It is essentially a raised granary built into the structure of the house itself and functioning as a second floor.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] It is commonly used to store sacred objects (like effigies of granary idols or deceased ancestors), heirlooms, and other important objects.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These areas are usually not part of the regular living space and may only be accessible to certain members of the family or after performing a specific ritual.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Other parts of the house may also be associated with certain deities, and thus certain activities like receiving guests or conducting marriage ceremonies can only be performed in specific areas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] While rice cultivation wasn't among the technologies carried into Remote Oceania, raised storehouses still survived.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The *pātaka* of the Māori people is an example.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The largest *pātaka* are elaborately adorned with carvings and are often the tallest buildings in the Māori *pā*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These were used to store implements, weapons, ships, and other valuables; while smaller *pātaka* were used to store provisions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] A special type of *pātaka*, supported by a single tall post, also had ritual importance and was used to isolate high-born children during their training for leadership.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The majority of Austronesian structures are not permanent.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They are made from perishable materials like wood, bamboo, plant fiber, and leaves.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Similar to traditional Austronesian boats, they do not use nails but are traditionally constructed solely by joints, weaving, ties, and dowels.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Elements of the structures are repaired and replaced regularly or as they get damaged.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Because of this, archaeological records of prehistoric Austronesian structures are usually limited to traces of house posts, with no way of determining the original building plans.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Indirect evidence of traditional Austronesian architecture, however, can be gleaned from their contemporary representations in art, such as friezes on the walls of later Hindu-Buddhist stone temples (like in reliefs at Borobudur and Prambanan).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] But these are limited to the recent centuries.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They can also be reconstructed linguistically from shared terms for architectural elements, like ridge poles, thatch, rafters, house posts, hearths, notched log ladders, storage racks, public buildings, and so on.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Linguistic evidence also makes it clear that stilt houses were already present among Austronesian groups since at least the Late Neolithic.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In modern Indonesia, varying styles are collectively known as *rumah adat*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Arbi *et al.* (2013) have also noted the striking similarities between Austronesian architecture and Japanese traditional raised architecture (*shinmei-zukuri*).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Particularly the buildings of the Ise Grand Shrine, which contrast with the pit-houses typical of the Neolithic Yayoi period.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They propose significant Neolithic contact between the people of southern Japan and Austronesians or pre-Austronesians that occurred prior to the spread of Han Chinese cultural influence to the islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Rice cultivation is also believed to have been introduced to Japan from a para-Austronesian group from coastal eastern China.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Waterson (2009) has also argued that the architectural tradition of stilt houses is originally Austronesian and that similar building traditions in Japan and mainland Asia (notably among Kra-Dai and Austroasiatic-speaking groups) correspond to contacts with a prehistoric Austronesian network.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Outside of Taiwan, assemblages of red-slipped pottery, plainware, and incised and stamped pottery associated with Austronesian migrations are first documented from around 2000 to 1800 BCE in the northern Philippines, from sites in the Batanes Islands and the Cagayan Valley of Northern Luzon.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] From there, pottery technology rapidly spread to the east, south, and southwest.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This type of pottery dispersed south and southwest to the rest of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The eastward and southward branches of the migrations converged in Island Melanesia, resulting in what is now known as the Lapita culture, centered around the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The oldest known pottery assemblages in Oceania are circle- and punctate/dentate-stamped pottery in the Marianas Islands, securely dated to 1500 BCE–1300 BCE from multiple archaeological sites.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] It predates the earliest Lapita culture pottery assemblages (c.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] 1350 –1300 BCE) and bears closest resemblance to a subset of the more diverse Nagsabaran pottery of the northern Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] It is currently disputed whether this is indicative of a direct ancient voyage from the northern Philippines to the Marianas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Hung *et al.* (2011) proposed a direct deliberate voyage from eastern Luzon, which would make it the longest sea crossing undertaken by that time in human history.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This has also been proposed by earlier authors like Blust (2000) and Reid (2002), based on linguistics.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Winter *et al.* (2012), on the other hand, dismissed the similarities as being generic rather than specific to the region.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] This is from both analysis of the microscopic structure of the shards (indicating manufacturing techniques) and the impossibility of drift voyaging from Luzon, due to the prevailing wind and currents.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Instead of a voyage directly from Luzon, they instead proposed an origin either from a direct single voyage from Mindanao (southern Philippines) or Morotai (Maluku Islands) to Guam; or two voyages, with way stations in Palau or Yap.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Hung *et al.* (2012) pointed out in response that no pottery assemblages older than 2,000 years old have been found in Morotai, which also has a Papuan-speaking population.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They also mentioned that present-day data on wind and currents is not a reliable way of ascertaining migration routes, and that the voyages settling Remote Oceania would have been deliberate, not uncontrolled drifting.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Similar presumptions by Thor Heyerdahl led to his erroneous conclusion that Polynesia was settled from the Americas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Pottery manufacturing techniques are also diverse, even within a single community.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Thus, analysis of manufacturing methods is less significant than comparison of decorative systems.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Nevertheless, Hung *et al.* (2012) emphasized that they also did not discount other sources (yet undiscovered) from the southern Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They also proposed the Eastern Visayas as a likely point of origin.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Sources south of the Philippines remain unlikely without further archaeological findings due to their related pottery assemblages being younger than 1500 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The dentate-stamped pottery of the Lapita culture (c.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] 1350–1300 BCE) retained elements also found in the Nagsabaran pottery in the Philippines, including stamped circles as well as the cross-in-circle motif.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They carried pottery technology as far as Tonga in Polynesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Pottery technology in Tonga, however, became reduced to undecorated plainware within only two centuries before abruptly disappearing completely by around 400 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Pottery was absent in subsequent migrations to the rest of Remote Oceania, being replaced instead with carved wooden or bamboo containers, bottle gourds, and baskets.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] However, the geometric designs and stylized figures used in the pottery are still present in other surviving art forms, such as tattooing, weaving, and barkcloth patterns.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] A common practice among Austronesians in a large area of Island Southeast Asia is the use of burial jars, which emerged during the Late Neolithic and flourished in the first millennium CE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They are characteristic of a region bordered by the Philippines to the north, southern Sumatra in the southwest, and Sumba and the Maluku Islands in the southeast.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] However, these didn't comprise a single tradition but can be grouped into at least fourteen different traditions scattered across the islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In most cases, the earliest burial jars used were large indigenous earthenware jars, followed by indigenous or imported stoneware jars (*martaban*), and finally imported porcelain jars acquired from the burgeoning maritime trade with China and Mainland Southeast Asia around the 14th century CE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Slit drums are indigenous Austronesian musical instruments invented and used by Southeast Asian-Austronesian and Oceanic-Austronesian ethnic groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Gong ensembles are also a common musical heritage of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The casting of gong instruments is believed to have originated from the Bronze Age cultures of Mainland Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] It spread to the Austronesian islands initially through trade as prestige goods.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] However, mainland Asian gongs were never used in ensembles; the innovation of using gong sets is uniquely Austronesian.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Gong ensembles are found in western Malayo-Polynesian groups, though they never penetrated much further east.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] There are roughly two gong ensemble traditions among Austronesians, which also produced gongs in ancient times.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In western Island Southeast Asia, these traditions are collectively known as *gamelan*, being centred on the island of Java in Indonesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They include the *celempung* of the Malay Peninsula, *talempung* of northern Sumatra, *caklempung* of central Sumatra, *chalempung* of southern Sumatra, *bonang* of Java, *kromong* of western Kalimantan, *engkromong* of Sarawak, and *trompong* of western Nusa Tenggara.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In eastern Island Southeast Asia, these traditions are known as *kulintang* and are centred in Mindanao and the Sulu archipelago of the southern Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They include the *kulintangan* of Sabah and Palawan, *kolintang* of northern Sulawesi, *kulintang* of Halmahera and Timor, and *totobuang* of the southern Maluku Islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] The ancestral pre-Austronesian Liangzhu culture (3400–2250 BCE) of the Yangtze River delta was one of the ancient centers of Neolithic jade carving.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Jade was spread to Taiwan by around 3,000 BCE, then further into the Philippines at 2,000 BCE and Vietnam at 1,800–1,500 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] All of them began to produce various tools and ornaments in indigenous jade workshops, including adzes, bracelets, beads, and rings.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These typically depicted two-headed animals or were ring-shaped with side projections.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They were indicative of a very active ancient maritime trading region, known as the Sa Huynh-Kalanay Interaction Sphere, that imported and exported raw jade and finished jade ornaments.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] They were produced during a period from 500 BCE to as late as 1000 CE, although later examples were replaced with metal, wood, bone, clay, green mica, black nephrite, or shell materials, rather than green jade.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Polished and ground stone adzes, gouges, and other implements, some of which are made from jade-like stone, have also been recorded in areas of Island Melanesia and eastern New Guinea associated with the Lapita culture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] These were considered valuable currency and were primarily used to trade for goods.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] In 2012, a Lapita jadeite gouge used for wood carving was found on Emirau Island in the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] It was dated to around 3,300 BCE, but the origin of the jade material is unknown.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p02] Similar stone tools have also been found in New Caledonia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Jade was absent in most of Remote Oceania, due to the lack of deposits.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, there is putative evidence that Polynesians may have remained familiar with jade and may acquired it through prehistoric trade contacts with New Caledonia, Island Melanesia, and/or New Zealand.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Jade-carving traditions reappeared among the Māori people of New Zealand.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These were produced from locally sourced *pounamu* (greenstone) and were used to produce *taonga* (treasure).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They include various tools and weapons like adzes, scrapers, fishing hooks, and *mere*, as well as ornaments like the *hei-tiki* and *hei matau*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Certain ornaments like the *pekapeka* (double-headed animal pendant) and the *kākā pōria* (bird leg ring) bear remarkably strong resemblances to the double-headed and ring-type *lingling‑o*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] There are approximately six to seven hundred rock art sites discovered in Southeast Asia and Island Melanesia, as well as over eight hundred megalithic sites.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The sites specifically associated with the Austronesian expansion contain examples of indigenous pictograms and petroglyphs.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Despite proximity, these traditions can be distinguished readily from the Australo-Melanesian rock art traditions of Australia (except the Torres Strait Islands) as well as the interior highlands of New Guinea, indicating the borders of the extent of the Austronesian expansion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Dating rock art is difficult, but some of the sites subjected to direct dating pre-date Austronesian arrival, like the Lene Hara paintings of East Timor, which have an age range of 6,300 to 26,000 BP.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Conversely, others are more recent and can be dated indirectly by their subjects.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The depictions of pottery, ships, and metal objects, for example, put certain rock art sites at a range of 2,000 to 4,000 BP.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Some hunter-gatherer groups have also continued to produce rock art well into the present period, as evidenced by their modern subjects.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The Megalithic Culture is mostly limited to western Island Southeast Asia, with the greatest concentration being western Indonesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] While most sites are not dated, the age ranges of dating sites are between the 2nd and 16th centuries CE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Prasetyo (2006) suggests that the megalithic traditions are not originally Austronesian but rather innovations acquired through trade with India and China, but this has little to no evidence in the intervening regions in Thailand, Vietnam, and the Philippines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The Austronesian Painting Traditions are the most common types of rock art in Island Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They consist of scenes and pictograms typically found in rock shelters and caves near coastal areas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They are characteristically rendered in red ocher pigments for the earlier forms, later sometimes superseded by paintings done in black charcoal pigments.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Their sites are mostly clustered in Eastern Indonesia and Island Melanesia, although a few examples can be found in the rest of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Their occurrence has a high correlation to Austronesian-speaking areas, further evidenced by the appearance of bronze artifacts in the paintings.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They are mostly found near the coastlines.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Their common motifs include hand stencils, "sun-ray" designs, boats, and active human figures with headdresses or weapons and other paraphernalia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They also feature geometric motifs similar to those of the Austronesian Engraving Style.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Some paintings are also associated with traces of human burials and funerary rites, including ship burials.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The representations of boats themselves are believed to be connected to the widespread "ship of the dead" Austronesian funerary practices.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The earliest APT site dated is from Vanuatu and was found to be around 3,000 BP, corresponding to the initial migration wave of the Austronesians.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These early sites are largely characterized by face motifs and hand stencils.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Later sites, from 1,500 BP onwards, however, begin to show regional divergence in their art styles.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] APT can be readily distinguished from older Pleistocene-era Australo-Melanesian cave paintings by their motifs, color, and composition, though they can often be found in the same locality.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The most recognizable motifs of APT (like boats) do not occur in cave paintings (or engravings) that definitely pre-date the Austronesian arrival—the sole exception being the stenciled hand motif.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Some APT examples are also characteristically found in relatively inaccessible locations, including very high up in cliffsides overlooking the sea.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] No traces of APT have been found in Taiwan or the Philippines, though there is continuity in the motifs of spirals and concentric circles found in ancestral petroglyphs.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] AES, which consists of petroglyphs carved into rock surfaces, is far less common than APT.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The majority of these sites are in coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] AES sites, which can be tentatively traced back to the similar Wanshan petroglyphs of Taiwan, are believed to be largely correlated to the prehistoric extent of the Lapita culture.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The common motif of this tradition is curvilinear geometric engravings like spirals, concentric circles, and face-like forms.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These resemble the geometric motifs in APT, though they are considered to be two separate artistic traditions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] AES is particularly dominant in the Solomon Islands and New Caledonia, where engravings are far more abundant than painted sites.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] O'Connor *et al.* (2015) proposes that APT developed during the initial rapid southward Austronesian expansion, and not before, possibly as a response to the communication challenges brought about by the new maritime mode of living.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The easternmost islands of Island Melanesia (Vanuatu, Fiji, and New Caledonia) are considered part of Remote Oceania, as they are beyond the inter-island visibility threshold.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These island groups begin to show divergence from the APT and AES traditions of Near Oceania.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] While their art traditions show a clear continuation of the APT and AES traditions, they also feature innovations unique to each island group, like the increasing use of black charcoal, rectilinear motifs, and being more commonly found inside sacred caves rather than on open cliffsides.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In Micronesia, the rock art traditions can be divided into three general regions: western, central, and eastern.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In western Micronesia (Palau, Yap, Guam, and the Northern Mariana Islands), rock art primarily consists of paintings on high cave ceilings and sea-facing cliffs.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] It is very similar to APT in terms of its motifs as well as its placement in relatively inaccessible locations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Common motifs include hand stencils, faces, turtles and fish, concentric circles, and characteristic four-pointed stars.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Petroglyphs are rare and mainly consist of human forms with triangular bodies without heads or arms.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] This is believed to be connected to the funerary rite of removing the heads from the bodies of deceased relatives.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A notable megalithic tradition in western Micronesia are the *haligi* stone pillars of the Chamorro people.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These are capped stone pillars that are believed to have served as supports for raised buildings.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They are associated with the Latte period (900 to 1700 CE), when a new wave of migrants from Southeast Asia reintroduced rice cultivation to the islands.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Another megalithic tradition is that of the rai stones, massive doughnut-shaped discs of rock that were used as currency on Yap.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Rock art in central Micronesia (Chuuk, Pohnpei, and Kosrae), in contrast, is dominated by rock engravings with motifs tying it to the rock art traditions of Island Melanesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They include curvilinear shapes like spirals and concentric circles, tree-like shapes, and the distinctive "enveloped cross" motif.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The Pohnpaid petroglyphs are the largest assemblage of rock engravings in the region, with motifs dominated by footprints, enveloped crosses, and outlined "sword-paddles".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Central Micronesia also hosts the ruins of the stone cities of Nan Madol (1,180–1,200 CE) and Leluh (1,200–1,800 CE), on the islands of Pohnpei and Kosrae, respectively.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In the low-lying atolls of eastern Micronesia, rock art is rare-to-nonexistent, due to the absence of suitable rock surfaces for painting or engraving.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In Polynesia, rock art is dominated by petroglyphs, rather than paintings, and they show less variation than the rock art of Near Oceania and ISEA.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In the western Polynesian islands nearest to Island Melanesia, rock art is rare (like in Tonga and Samoa) or absent entirely (like in the Cook Islands).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, petroglyphs are abundant on the islands in the further reaches of the Polynesian triangle, particularly on Hawaii, the Marquesas, and Rapa Nui.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Rapa Nui has the densest concentration of engravings in Polynesia as a whole, while the Puʻuloa petroglyphs site on Hawaii has the largest number of petroglyphs in a single site, at over 21,000 engravings.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Polynesia also features megalithic sacred ceremonial centers generally known as *marae*.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] On Tonga and Samoa, the existing rock art sites consist mostly of engravings with motifs including curvilinear shapes, human figures, "jellyfish", turtles, birds, and footprints.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These are typically carved in natural rock formations or *marae* sites.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In the central-eastern Polynesian islands, which include the Marquesas and the Society Islands, petroglyphs are more numerous.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They show the archetypal Polynesian motifs of turtles, faces, cup-like depressions (cupules), stick-like human figures, boats, fish, curvilinear shapes, and concentric circles.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Like in western Polynesia, they are typically carved into *marae* sites or in rocks beside streams.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The existing rock paintings also display the same motifs but are rendered in different styles.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] On the Hawaiian islands, the abundant petroglyphs are remarkably all similar in execution.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Their common subjects include stick-like human figures, dogs, boats, sails, paddles, footprints, and ceremonial headdresses.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Depictions of marine life, however, are rare, unlike in the rest of Polynesia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They are typically carved into boulders, lava rock formations, and cliffsides.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Red paintings of dogs on cliffsides and caves can also be found on Kauʻai and Maui.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The megalithic traditions of Hawaii can be exemplified by the *heiau* sacred sites, which can range from simple earth terraces to standing stones.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] On Rapa Nui, the engravings are distinctive but still show similarities to the techniques and motifs of the Marquesas.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Their motifs commonly include disembodied parts of the human body (vulvae in particular), animals, plants, ceremonial objects, and boats.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A prominent motif is also that of the "birdman" figure, which is associated with the *tangata manu* cult of Makemake.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The best-known rock art assemblage of Rapa Nui, however, are the *moai* megaliths.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A few paintings, mostly of birds and boats, have also been discovered, which are associated with the engravings, rather than being separate artforms.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The rock art in New Zealand can be divided into two regions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] North Island features more engravings than paintings, while South Island is unique in that it is the only Polynesian island where there are more paintings than engravings.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] New Zealand rock paintings are done in red and black pigments and can sometimes be found at inaccessible heights.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They typically depict human figures (particularly a front-facing human figure with flexed arms), birds, lizards, dogs, fish, and what has been identified as "birdmen".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Engravings in open spaces like cliffsides are generally of spirals and curvilinear shapes, while engravings in enclosed caves and shelters depict faces and boats.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The same motifs can also be seen in dendroglyphs on living trees.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These were symbols of status and rank as well as being considered marks of beauty.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] She is probably of Mixed-white ancestry common amongst Maori people, because to her caucasian facial features.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Body art among Austronesian peoples is common, especially elaborate tattooing, which is one of the most well-known pan-Austronesian traditions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In modern times, tattoos are usually associated with Polynesian culture, due to the highly influential accounts of James Cook in his explorations of the Pacific in the 18th century.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Cook introduced the word "tattoo" (archaic: "tattaow", "tattow") into the English vocabulary from Tahitian and Samoan *tātau* ("to tap").
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, tattoos existed prominently in various other Austronesian groups prior to contact with other cultures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Tattoos had various functions among Austronesian societies.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Among men, they were strongly linked to the widespread practice of head-hunting raids.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In head-hunting societies, tattoos were records of how many heads the warrior had taken in battle, and they were part of the initiation rites into adulthood.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The number and location of tattoos, therefore, were indicative of a warrior's status and prowess.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Among the Indigenous Taiwanese, tattoos were present for both men and women.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Among the Atayal, facial tattoos were dominant.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They indicated maturity and skill in weaving and farming for women and skill in hunting and battle for men.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] As in most of Austronesia, tattooing traditions in Taiwan have largely disappeared due to the Sinicization of native peoples after the Chinese colonization of the island in the 17th century, as well as conversion to Christianity.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Most of the remaining tattoos are only found among elders.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] One of the earliest descriptions of Austronesian tattoos by Europeans was during the 16th-century Spanish expeditions to the Philippines, beginning with the first voyage of circumnavigation by Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The Spanish encountered the heavily tattooed Visayan people in the Visayas Islands, whom they named the *Pintados* (Spanish for "the painted ones").
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, Philippine tattooing traditions (*batok*) have mostly been lost as the natives of the islands converted to Christianity and Islam, though they are still practiced in isolated groups in the highlands of Luzon and Mindanao.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Philippine tattoos were usually geometric patterns or stylized depictions of animals, plants, and human figures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Some of the few remaining traditional tattoos in the Philippines are among elders of the Igorot peoples.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Most of these were records of war exploits against the Japanese during World War II.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Among the Māori of New Zealand, tattoos (*moko*) were originally carved into the skin using bone chisels (*uhi*) rather than through puncturing, as in usual practice.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In addition to being pigmented, the skin was also left raised into ridges of swirling patterns.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Teeth blackening was the custom of dyeing one's teeth black with various tannin-rich plant dyes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] It was practiced throughout almost the entire range of Austronesia, including Island Southeast Asia, Madagascar, Micronesia, and Island Melanesia, reaching as far east as Malaita.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] It also existed in non-Austronesian populations in Mainland Southeast Asia and Japan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The practice was primarily preventative, as it reduced the chances of developing tooth decay, similar to modern dental sealants.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] It also had cultural significance and was seen as beautiful.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A common sentiment was that blackened teeth separated humans from animals.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] For example in Bali, Indonesia, **Potong gigi**, also known as **mesangih** or **mepandes**, is a form of ritual body modification of adolescents, typically teenagers, in parts of Bali that involves the filing of the canine teeth.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The religious traditions of the Austronesian people focus mostly on ancestral spirits, nature spirits, and gods, making it a complex animistic religion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Mythologies vary by culture and geographical location but share common basic aspects, such as ancestor worship, animism, shamanism, and the belief in a spirit world and powerful deities.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] There is also a great amount of shared mythology and a common belief in Mana.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Many of these beliefs have gradually been replaced.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Examples of native religions include: Indigenous Philippine folk religions (including beliefs in Anito), Sunda Wiwitan, Kejawen, Kaharingan, and Māori religion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Many Austronesian religious beliefs have been incorporated into foreign religions, such as Hinduism, Buddhism, Christianity, and Islam, which Austronesian peoples were introduced to later.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] With the possible exception of rongorongo on Rapa Nui, Austronesians did not have an indigenous writing system but rather adopted or developed writing systems after contact with various non-Austronesian cultures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] There existed various forms of symbolic communication using pictograms and petroglyphs, but these did not encode language.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Rongorongo, said to have originally been called *kohau motu mo rongorongo* ("lines of inscriptions for chanting out"), is the only pre-contact indigenous Austronesian system of glyphs that appear to be true writing or at least proto-writing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They consist of around 120 glyphs, ranging from representations of plants to animals, celestial objects, and geometric shapes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They were inscribed into wooden tablets about 12 to 20 in (30 to 51 cm) long using shark teeth and obsidian flakes.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The wood allegedly came from toromiro and makoʻi trees, which is notable given that Rapa Nui was completely deforested at the time of European contact.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Of the surviving two dozen tablets, a few were made from trees introduced after European contact, as well as wood originating from European ships and driftwood.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Rapa Nui also has a rich assemblage of petroglyphs largely associated with the *tangata manu* ("birdman") cult of Makemake.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Although some rongorongo glyphs may have been derived from these petroglyphs, rongorongo does not appear in any of the abundant rock carvings in Rapa Nui and seems to be restricted to the wooden tablets.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The tablets were first described by an outsider in 1864 by the Catholic missionary Eugène Eyraud, who said they were found "in all the houses".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, he paid them little attention, and they remained unnoticed by the outside world.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] It wasn't until 1869 that one of the tablets came into the possession of Florentin-Étienne Jaussen, the Bishop of Tahiti.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] He brought the tablets to the world's attention and instructed the Rapa Nui mission to gather more information about them.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] But by then, most of the tablets were allegedly already destroyed, presumed to have been used as fuel by the natives on the deforested island.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] At the time of discovery of the tablets, Rapa Nui had undergone severe depopulation.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] This was largely due to the loss of the island's last trees and the Peruvian and Chilean slave raids in the early 1860s.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The literate ruling classes of the Rapa Nui people (including the royal family and the religious caste) and the majority of the island's population were kidnapped or killed in the slave raids.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Most of those taken died after only one or two years in captivity from harsh working conditions and European diseases.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Succeeding epidemics of smallpox and tuberculosis further decimated the island's population to the point that there were not enough people to bury the dead.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The last remnants of the Rapa Nui people were assimilated by the Tahitians who were later brought to the island in an effort to repopulate it, further resulting in the loss of most of the Old Rapa Nui language.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Oral tradition holds that the ruling classes were the only ones who could read the tablets, and the ability to decipher the tablets was lost along with them.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Numerous attempts have been made to read the tablets, starting from a few years after their discovery.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] But to this day, none have proven successful.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Some authors have proposed that rongorongo may have been an attempt to imitate European script after the idea of writing was introduced during the "signing" of the 1770 Spanish Treaty of Annexation or through knowledge of European writing acquired elsewhere.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They cite various reasons, including the lack of attestation of rongorongo prior to the 1860s, the clearly more recent provenance of some of the tablets, the lack of antecedents, and the lack of additional archaeological evidence since its discovery.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Others argue that it was merely a mnemonic list of symbols meant to guide incantations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Whether rongorongo is merely an example of trans-cultural diffusion or a true indigenous Austronesian writing system (and one of the few independent inventions of writing in human history) remains unknown.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In Southeast Asia, the first true writing systems of pre-modern Austronesian cultures were all derived from the Grantha and Pallava Brahmic scripts, all of which are abugidas from South India.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Various forms of abugidas spread throughout Austronesian cultures in Southeast Asia as kingdoms became Indianized through early maritime trading.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The oldest use of abugida scripts in Austronesian cultures are 4th-century stone inscriptions written in Cham, from Vietnam.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] There are numerous other Brahmic-derived writing systems among Southeast Asian Austronesians, usually specific to a certain ethnic group.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Notable examples include Balinese, Batak, Baybayin, Buhid, Hanunó'o, Javanese, Kulitan, Lontara, Old Kawi, Rejang, Rencong, Sundanese, and Tagbanwa.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They vary from having letters with rounded shapes to characters with sharp cuneiform-like angles, as a result of the difference in writing mediums, with the former being ideal for writing on soft leaves and the latter on bamboo panels.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The use of the scripts ranged from mundane records to encoding esoteric knowledge on magico-religious rituals and folk medicine.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In regions that converted to Islam, abjads derived from the Arabic script started replacing the earlier abugidas at around the 13th century in Southeast Asia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Madagascar adopted the Arabic script in the 14th century.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Abjads, however, have an even greater inherent problem with encoding Austronesian languages than abugidas, because Austronesian languages have more varied and salient vowels that the Arabic script usually cannot encode.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] As a result, the Austronesian adaptations such as the Jawi and the Pegon scripts have been modified with a system of diacritics that encode sounds, both vowels and consonants, native to Austronesian languages but absent in Semitic ones.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] With the advent of the Colonial Era, almost all of these writing systems have been replaced with alphabets adapted from the Latin, as in the Hawaiian, Filipino, and Malay alphabet.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, several Formosan languages had been written in zhuyin, and Cia-Cia off Sulawesi has experimented with hangul.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] On Woleai and surrounding islands, a script was developed for the Woleaian language in the early 20th century.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Approximately 20% of the script's letterforms were borrowed from Latin letters; the remaining characters seem to have been derived from indigenous iconography.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Despite this heavy Latin influence, the script was a syllabary.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Vanuatu has a unique tradition of sand drawing, in which images are created by a single continuous line drawn in the sand.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] It is believed to have functioned as a means of symbolic communication in pre-contact Island Melanesia, especially between travelers and ethnic groups that do not speak the same language.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The sand drawings consist of around 300 different designs and seem to be shared across language groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In the 1990s, elements of the drawings were adapted into a modern constructed script called Avoiuli by the Turaga indigenous movement on Pentecost Island.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Genetic studies have been conducted on Austronesian peoples.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Haplogroup O1a, marked by the M119 SNP, is frequently detected in native Taiwanese and northern Filipinos, as well as some people in Indonesia, Malaysia, and non-Austronesian populations in southern China.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A 2007 analysis of the DNA recovered from human remains in archaeological sites of prehistoric peoples along the Yangtze River in China also shows high frequencies of Haplogroup O1 in the Neolithic Liangzhu culture, linking them to Austronesian and Tai-Kadai peoples.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The Liangzhu culture existed in coastal areas around the mouth of the Yangtze.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Haplogroup O1 was absent in other archaeological sites inland.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The authors of the study suggest that this may be evidence of two different human migration routes during the peopling of Eastern Asia; one coastal and the other inland, with little gene flow between them.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The 'core Austronesian' population derives more ancestry from Late Neolithic Fujian-related sources (66.9%–74.3%), similar to present Kra-Dai groups and southeastern Han Chinese.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Strong affinities also exist between present Austronesians and Qihe3 from Early Neolithic Fujian.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Qihe3 clusters with Boshan from Early Neolithic Shandong and is genetically indistinguishable from Liangdao-2.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, Qihe3 could be modeled as a mixture of local ancestries from southeastern China with some input from northeastern China.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In contrast, Late Neolithic Fujianese populations, like Xitoucun and Tanshishan, have higher affinities with Dushan-related populations, who have slightly more affinities for present Austroasiatic-speaking groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Likewise, the Taiwan Hanben population is closely related to Dushan-related populations and are related to the Taiwan Gongguan population, Longli Bouyei and Qiandongnan Dong, who are representatives of the ancestral Kra-Dai population, Kinh Vietnamese etc.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Another study states affirms the southeastern Chinese origins of the 'proto-Austronesian' population although there's evidence that they mixed with contemporary populations from Shandong.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Using the Atayal as proxies for the ancestral Austronesian population, they can also be modeled as a mixture of North Indian-related (6%) and Naxi/Miao-related groups (94%).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] An important breakthrough in studies in Austronesian genetics was the identification of the "Polynesian motif" (haplogroup B4a1a1) in 1989, a specific nine-base-pair deletion mutation in mitochondrial DNA.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Several studies have shown that it is shared by Polynesians and Island Southeast Asians, with a sub-branch also identified in Madagascar, indicating shared maternal ancestry among Austronesians.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] This indicates that the Lapita people, the direct ancestors of Polynesians, were likely matrilocal, assimilating Papuan men from outside the community by marriage in Near Oceania, prior to the Polynesian expansion into Remote Oceania.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Moodley *et al.* (2009) identified two distinct populations of the gut bacteria *Helicobacter pylori* that accompanied human migrations into Island Southeast Asia and Oceania, called hpSahul and hspMāori.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The study sampled Native Australians, Native Taiwanese, highlanders in New Guinea, and Melanesians and Polynesians in New Caledonia, which were then compared with other *H. pylori* haplotypes from Europeans, Asians, Pacific Islanders, and others.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The study found hspMāori from Native Taiwanese, Melanesians, Polynesians, and two inhabitants from the Torres Strait Islands, all of which are Austronesian sources.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] As expected, hspMāori showed greatest genetic diversity in Taiwan, while all non-Taiwanese hspMāori populations belonged to a single lineage they called the "Pacific clade".
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They also calculated the isolation-with-migration model (IMa), which showed that the divergence of the Pacific clade of hspMāori was unidirectional from Taiwan to the Pacific.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] This is consistent with the Out-of-Taiwan model of Austronesian expansion.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A 2014 study states that Austronesian populations from Island Southeast Asia and Oceania, such as Fiji and Polynesia, have 30-90% Taiwan-related ancestry.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Populations from western Island Southeast Asia have ~10–60% H'tin-related ancestry, with the rest being Taiwan-related and Negrito-related.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] In contrast, there is no Taiwan-related ancestry in admixed Mainland Southeast Asian populations that don't traditionally speak Austronesian languages.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The company's scientists surmised that this was due to the shared Austronesian genetic heritage being incorrectly identified as Filipino ancestry.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] According to a 2021 study, Cordillerans are the least admixed Austronesian group among the Austronesians of East Asia, especially Kankanaey, Bontoc, Balangao, Tuwali, Ayangan, Kalanguya, and Ibaloi groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Compared to Austronesians like Ami and Atayal, they do not exhibit admixture with Austroasiatic-related and Northeast Asian-related groups.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] All Filipino subgroups likewise show closer affinities to Cordillerans than Ami and Atayal.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Nonetheless, Ami, Atayal and Cordillerans all share strong affinities with Malaysians, Indonesians, Oceanians and even ancient individuals from peninsular Malaysia and Oceanian Lapita.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Cordillerans are also closely related to the ~7,000 to 8,000-y-old Liangdao-2 individual and did not receive the northern East Asian ancestry that was introduced in this individual.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Compared to other Filipino subgroups, Central Cordillerans show no admixture with indigenous Negritos despite extensive interaction with their neighbors.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, there's evidence of northern East Asian ancestry being introduced to the Batanes Islands and coastal regions of Luzon after the initial Cordilleran settlement of the Philippines from Taiwan.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A 2023 study, however, states that present Kankanaey groups have about ~33% northern East Asian ancestry, similar to what's found in Taiwan Highland/Taiwan Orchid Island groups, who have ~28–37% northern East Asian ancestry.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These findings suggest considerable northern East Asian influence in Taiwan prior to the Out-of-Taiwan expansions.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] For example, other early Out-of-Taiwan (i.e.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Lapita) groups have more northern East Asian ancestry than Into-Taiwan groups (~21–29% vs. ~0–8%).
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Austronesian-related populations also partially contributed to the genomes of Jōmon peoples and Koreans.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] However, the affinities between Austronesians and Jōmon more likely reflect shared descent or genetic input from the Jōmon into Austronesians themselves.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Other studies show no significant gene flow from Austronesians to the Jōmon, including Ryukyuan Jōmon.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The Austronesian migrations were accompanied by a set of domesticated, semi-domesticated, and commensal plants and animals transported via outrigger ships and catamarans that enabled early Austronesians to thrive in their mostly island environments.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Some of these plants are sometimes also known as "canoe plants", especially in the context of Polynesian migrations.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] They provide another source of evidence for Austronesian population movements.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Notable examples of these crops include coconuts, bananas, rice, sugarcane, paper mulberry (tapa tree), breadfruit, taro, ube, areca nut (including the practice of betel chewing), ginger, turmeric, candlenut, pandan, and citruses.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The cultivation of sweet potatoes in Polynesia may also be evidence of prehistoric Austronesian contact with the Americas, though this remains disputed.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] The domesticated animals carried in Austronesian voyages include dogs, pigs, and chickens.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Austronesians also introduced these crops and domesticated animals westward via trade links.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] Island Southeast Asians established spice trade links with the Dravidian-speaking regions in Sri Lanka and Southern India by around 1500 to 600 BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] These early contacts resulted in the introduction of Austronesian crops and material culture to South Asia, including betel nut chewing, coconuts, sandalwood, domesticated bananas, sugarcane, cloves, and nutmeg.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] South Asian crops like the mung bean and horsegram were also present in Southeast Asia by 400–100 BCE, indicating the exchange was reciprocal.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] There is also indirect evidence of very early Austronesian contacts with Africa, based on the presence and spread of Austronesian domesticates like bananas, taro, chickens, and purple yam in Africa in the first millennium BCE.
[src:austronesian-peoples/austronesian-peoples-p03] A genomic analysis in 2020 showed Austronesian contact with South America around 1150–1200 CE, the earliest one being between Fatu Hiva and Colombia.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:austronesian-peoples/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:austronesian-peoples/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
